messages.messageBody:
I was going to send this to Pam Sorooshian and her daughter Rose
anyway, but I thought maybe there are others on this list who'd be
interested.

Last night at my house we had a discussion on maps and mapping.
(Wednesdays in winter people come over for discussions, SCA-based,
Renaissance and medieval topics.) This is the follow-up. The
websites deal with other than very-early maps.

Sometimes map reading is the portal to all KINDS of things you'd
never expect.
================================================================

http://www.booktv.org/program.aspx?
ProgramId=8860&SectionName=History&PlayMedia=No

http://kelsocartography.com/blog/?p=113

Annaliese send these links to the program I told you about.

-=-I know this is late, but this article ...-=-
It's never too late! We'll all be learning about this stuff for the
rest of our lives.

And Gunwaldt wanted me to send you the link to Strange Maps
http://strangemaps.wordpress.com/

Sandra
